Overview

NTD-302 is a high-voltage analog overdrive/distortion pedal featuring the Nutube 6P1, a revolutionary vacuum fluorescent display (VFD)â€“based triode device that reproduces true vacuum-tube behavior in an ultra-compact, low-power format.

This project is both a tribute and an exploration â€” a modern reinterpretation of tube saturation, created entirely in discrete analog circuitry.

---

Acknowledgement

This technology would not exist without the pioneering work of Fumio Saegusa (KORG) and Noritake Itron Corporation, who jointly developed the Nutube device.
As of 2026, Nutube celebrates its 10th anniversary (released September 23, 2016) and remarkably continues to be sold in Japan for the same price â€” Â¥5,500 JPY (tax-included) â€” unchanged since launch, despite severe global inflation.

Interestingly, although Nutube was originally expected to replace traditional vacuum tubes after the Ukraine-related supply crisis, most audio communities concluded that Nutube was not a simple drop-in replacement.
Why?

Because Nutube introduces fundamentally different electrical requirements:

â€¢ Filament voltage must be tightly controlled (damage occurs above 0.7 V)
â€¢ Grid bias must be driven by positive voltage
â€¢ Anode voltage requires â‰¥12 V for proper performance (30 V is ideal)
â€¢ Requires three separate regulated rails (30 V / 9 V / 5 V)
â€¢ Demands strict grounding topology and noise isolation

These factors made Nutube development knowledge-heavy, power-sensitive, and electrically unforgiving â€” leading many designers to abandon the device prematurely.

NTD-302 exists to prove that Nutube can be the star â€” not a gimmick.

---

Circuit Concept

NTD-302 uses both triode sections of a single Nutube 6P1, connected in true serial amplification and driven by a regulated 30 V anode supply.

Signal flow:
JFET buffer â†’ Nutube stage 1 â†’ Nutube stage 2 â†’ transistor buffer â†’ frequency-dependent gain network â†’ output volume

Unlike conventional distortion circuits, gain is not primarily voltage-based â€” it is frequency-selective.
A unique RC low-pass network performs tone-dependent amplification: reducing treble simultaneously increases perceived drive and thickness, producing a naturally compressed and creamy distortion character.

The final emitter stage introduces frequency shaping that allows:

â€¢ Sparkling Strat-style bite
â€¢ Thick humbucker-like low-end punch
â€¢ Wide dynamic response
â€¢ Extremely low noise floor

This pedal offers a fully analog, high-voltage Nutube distortion voice with fast attack, warm compression, and rich even-order harmonics.

